This place is the epitome much of what is wrong with Chicago and America today.  Let me start by going over the good points. Location and view.  Beyond that the place is a -10.  Food mediocre.  Drinks: bad  They have spent a lot of time/energy and money by creating "artificial scarcity" by (massivey) cutting down the number of seats and tables. The aceess to the place is horrendous.  The waste of space is "in your face" and deliberate. Large open spaces with few tables and manufactured lines.  Is sad to see that impresses so many people today.  Chicago is what it is due partly to making the strip of land by Lake Michigan public.  This place gives the flying middle finger to that history and revels in "ugly American wasting precious land and resources" thinking. If you want to make a statement about how little you care about global warming and wasteful destruction of resources then go here.  And the food and drinks are bad.

Great place to see good locally produced top notch Chicago plays at a very reasonable price  by lake front. It's housed in recently renovated building at Fullerton by the lake which it shares with a restaurant by the same name. The theater is run by the Chicago Park District, hence the reasonable price of shows. The restaurant is privately run. Both venues operate year round (at least that's the plan). It will be interesting to see the frozen lake right outside the windows while be warm and cozy enjoying meals and/or catching some plays indoor.
